(16, 431, 'Shameer Shah', 'shameer@businessbanter.com', 'http://www.businessbanter.com/', '2.102.167.85', '2012-12-29 17:27:00', '2012-12-29 17:27:00', 'Hi Chris, this is a wonderful post! Some great stats and brainstorm ideas you have provided here. I have had clients who ask me whether email marketing''s dead? I can''t imagine why they would ask that, apart from something that tells me it''s not working for them! They''re doing it all wrong and I have seen it with my own eyes. This is a good post to direct them to.\n\n\nThanks for sharing!', 0, '1', 'Disqus/1.1(2.77):750725773', '', 0, 0),
(17, 431, 'chexton', 'chris@getvero.com', '', '101.175.199.147', '2012-12-30 00:39:00', '2012-12-30 00:39:00', 'Thanks for the kind comment Shameer. I certainly think that there are lots of ways to improve on traditional email marketing and there is no doubt it''s a direct channel to the customer! This is a great example from Maria of successful email marketing :).', 0, '1', 'Disqus/1.1(2.77):751056759', '', 16, 0),
(18, 439, 'staticsteven', 'sritchie.ivey@gmail.com', '', '208.118.126.74', '2013-01-29 22:15:00', '2013-01-29 22:15:00', 'I think a possibility (if I look specifically at the Lego bundle) is that I don''t even want the added bonus. Chances are it isn''t free either (even if you end up saving, you are paying for something you don''t need). It is possible that the same thing happens with other bundles, sure I only pay X more for 20 more products, but why pay extra at all if I don''t want/need any of the extras?', 0, '1', 'Disqus/1.1(2.77):782453000', '', 0, 0),
(19, 439, 'Guest', 'anonymized-783082045@disqus.com', '', '121.210.168.190', '2013-01-30 11:41:00', '2013-01-30 11:41:00', 'Totally Steven - the idea is totally to challenge the notion of ''more is better''. Just because you are technically throwing more in the bundle hardly means you are satisfying people''s actual needs. As you point out, you might be actively deterring them!\n\n\nNice one :).', 0, '1', 'Disqus/1.1(2.77):783082045', '', 0, 0),
(20, 439, 'Ethan Cantil-Voorhees', 'ethancv@gmail.com', '', '72.14.229.81', '2013-01-30 20:41:00', '2013-01-30 20:41:00', 'In general, a cool article.\n\nHowever, be careful with your examples; there''s more then one layer to most bundles.\n\nFor instance, in the camera bundle, the accessories essentially cost nothing (and have a huge margin), while the camera has a tiny margin.  Buy.com likely couldn''t discount the camera, on it''s own, more then a few %.  However, bundling with the accessories lets them claim a discount and sell a bunch of high-margin gear.', 0, '1', 'Disqus/1.1(2.77):783672505', '', 0, 0),
(21, 439, 'chexton', 'chris@getvero.com', '', '59.167.66.200', '2013-01-31 03:41:00', '2013-01-31 03:41:00', 'Ethan - thanks!\n\nI definitely agree with what you''ve said here. I interpreted the study as suggesting that, despite the gains from the businesses perspective (i.e. being able to discount thanks to the high profit margin on the accessories), this can in fact turn consumers off.\n\nPerhaps it''d be better to run with no discount, or a small discount, on the camera! Either way it adds another data point to think about when it comes to customer behaviour :).', 0, '1', 'Disqus/1.1(2.77):784083444', '', 20, 0),
