(110, 928, 'Owen McGab Enaohwo', 'oenaohwo@hireyourvirtualassistant.com', '', '139.85.223.10', '2013-07-09 14:19:00', '2013-07-09 14:19:00', 'What do you do emailwise if someone signs up for your blog email list for educational materials and then at the same time signs up for the free trial?\n\n\nHow does the lifecycle email sequence work in such a situation?', 0, '1', 'Disqus/1.1(2.77):956319943', '', 0, 0),
(111, 928, 'Travis Biziorek', 'tbiziorek@gmail.com', 'http://www.kibin.com/', '173.239.76.85', '2013-07-11 18:32:00', '2013-07-11 18:32:00', 'Nice post, Chris. As we''ve been planning our lifecycle marketing campaigns, there''s a LOT of thought that needs to go into what you''re sending and why you''re sending it.  Our abandoned cart campaign, for example, stretches some 30+ days and trickles emails that are designed to answer common questions we''ve received. It''s still early as we just launched this the other week. \n\n\nFor us, we don''t receive a user''s email until just before purchase. That means, we can''t begin reaching out until/if they abandon the cart. What should prove to be really interesting is sending out different emails to those users who haven''t come back in awhile to complete a purchase. We''re working on that now, and that could make some good blog fodder. \n\n\nCheers!\n\n\nTravis', 0, '1', 'Disqus/1.1(2.77):958942459', '', 0, 0),
(112, 928, 'chexton', 'chris@getvero.com', '', '38.96.132.29', '2013-07-17 20:24:00', '2013-07-17 20:24:00', 'I know you''ve been putting in the hard yards on your campaigns Travis so keen to see the awesome results :). I''d definitely be interested to hear how the different emails go and their timelines. If you''re willing to share at some point I think everyone could learn a lot as well!', 0, '1', 'Disqus/1.1(2.77):966123654', '', 111, 0),
(113, 928, 'chexton', 'chris@getvero.com', '', '38.96.132.29', '2013-07-17 20:25:00', '2013-07-17 20:25:00', 'Hi Owen, that''s a tricky one. You can easily add a filter in Vero or similar to ensure customers only get a campaign if they aren''t already receiving another. \n\n\nHaving said that it really depends what is in each sequence and how many emails are in each. I aim for no more than three emails per week and, even if a customer were to subscribe to all of the available material at Vero, it''s unlikely they''d get more than four (at a stretch) so it comes down to assessing your individual situation. More than happy to chat more if you''d like to. chrish@getvero.com :).', 0, '1', 'Disqus/1.1(2.77):966126233', '', 110, 0),
