(158, 1076, 'chexton', 'chris@getvero.com', '', '59.167.66.200', '2013-10-24 22:54:00', '2013-10-24 22:54:00', 'Stevie - that''s a massive compliment. Thanks!  As to your comment, I''d love to learn a little more (chris@getvero.com if you''d like) but my general answer is: of course you know enough about the industry. 9.9 times out of 10 when I talk to people with this fear, they usually have a fair bit of experience preparing content or ideas in the space they''re in and it''s usually worth putting together the best emails you can (even 2-3 at first) and get them out there. You''ll usually be surprised by how well received they are man!', 0, '1', 'Disqus/1.1(2.77):1095797583', '', 154, 0),
(159, 1123, 'Damian Thompson', 'damian@linchpin.net', 'http://www.linchpin.net/', '121.54.58.247', '2013-10-30 12:49:00', '2013-10-30 12:49:00', 'Hey Chris, great article.\n\n\nI agree wholeheartedly on #1 &amp; #2 and see it often. I think #3 might be wrong but think that it''s much harder to test.\n\n\nA single headline test is not a great sample size as wording in such a short headline can impact it so much. But would be interesting to see what it looks like across all of the Vero users possibly?\n\n\nNFI how you would actually pull that off though mate? :)', 0, '1', 'Disqus/1.1(2.77):1102119194', '', 0, 0),
(160, 1123, 'Dan Norris', 'dan@webcontrolroom.com', 'http://wpcurve.com/', '120.151.216.30', '2013-10-30 23:32:00', '2013-10-30 23:32:00', 'Solid Chris I''m guessing the Hitchcock one intrigues the wrong kind of people. People who want to know the answer to the question but aren''t really interested in growing their email list. Those people are attracted to the first headline not just to open it and get the answer but to learn more by clicking on the email. \n\n\nSolid post. Would you say the single CTA is still a useful general rule as long as you don''t have an email with a range of options like those presented? Like it you write 2 posts in a week are you better just sending 1 email about one of them with 1 CTA. Or better to send both in the one email. I''m still thinking option 1 would be better? I guess the answer is to test.', 0, '1', 'Disqus/1.1(2.77):1102949398', '', 0, 0),
(161, 650, 'Dan', 'plugintodan@gmail.com', '', '173.228.44.210', '2013-10-31 00:32:00', '2013-10-31 00:32:00', 'Mailchimp wrote a blog post that shocked me a bit -- they''re saying at least with their customers, boring and basic subject lines significantly outperform creative and catchy attempts. I can''t believe that''s the truth! Feel like I''ve heard the opposite. Any thoughts?\n\n\nHere''s the piece: http://mailchimp.com/resources/research/email-marketing-subject-line-comparison/', 0, '1', 'Disqus/1.1(2.77):1103004743', '', 0, 0),
(162, 650, 'chexton', 'chris@getvero.com', '', '202.0.106.130', '2013-10-31 00:42:00', '2013-10-31 00:42:00', 'that''s very interesting. thanks for the link! funny that you mentioned this as i just posted something today addressing this very issue: http://blog.getvero.com/3-supposed-best-practices-in-email-optimisation-debunked/', 0, '1', 'Disqus/1.1(2.77):1103012531', '', 161, 0),
(163, 1123, 'chexton', 'chris@getvero.com', '', '202.0.106.130', '2013-10-31 00:43:00', '2013-10-31 00:43:00', 'Yes, #3 is interesting. It''d be hard to ''normalize'' results across our users as there will be so much variance...though a report of that nature would be SUPER interesting. \n\n\nI''m open to ideas ;).', 0, '1', 'Disqus/1.1(2.77):1103013519', '', 159, 0),
(164, 1123, 'chexton', 'chris@getvero.com', '', '202.0.106.130', '2013-10-31 00:45:00', '2013-10-31 00:45:00', 'Yeah, I think the answer is to test. I would still use a single CTA as a general rule...but then it depends on the goal and format. I have done a little testing with our list and they don''t enjoy summary posts or ''link lists'' as much as they do single posts.\n\nIn contrast, an extremely cool example  of a newsletter that I believe has excellent engagement comes from the guys at NativeDigital: http://us1.campaign-archive1.com/?u=cae68b6d22429338227284384&amp;id=11940f9743&amp;e=05027a3acd\n\n\n\nI do think that in my example there is a specific use-case, as with Quibb, etc...though any content marketer could appropriate those. New ideas for us all to test hopefully!', 0, '1', 'Disqus/1.1(2.77):1103015242', '', 160, 0),
(165, 1123, 'Damian Thompson', 'damian@linchpin.net', 'http://www.linchpin.net/', '121.54.58.242', '2013-10-31 01:21:00', '2013-10-31 01:21:00', 'Hey I don''t solve problems I just point them out! ;)\n\nThe individual copywriting choices will factor so much in these I am unsure how you could test it other than a HUGE sample size...?', 0, '1', 'Disqus/1.1(2.77):1103044902', '', 163, 0),
(166, 1123, 'Jonathan Heston', 'insometry@gmail.com', '', '99.163.29.184', '2013-10-31 01:47:00', '2013-10-31 01:47:00', 'Good Stuff Chris. \n\nEveryone has a different market. (Well...not always true). But yeah. \nWhat works for Bob''s market might not work for mine. \nIt seems like nothing beats working your own tests. :)', 0, '1', 'Disqus/1.1(2.77):1103065774', '', 0, 0),
(167, 1123, 'chexton', 'chris@getvero.com', '', '59.167.66.200', '2013-10-31 02:43:00', '2013-10-31 02:43:00', 'Exactly - you''ve said it better than me ;). B2B, B2C, young audience, old audience, here, there...it all adds up. That''s why we''re trying to make testing easier and easier :).\n\n\nGlad you liked the post man.', 0, '1', 'Disqus/1.1(2.77):1103124262', '', 166, 0),
