(212, 1204, 'Omar Duarte', 'omarduarte@gmail.com', '', '200.88.252.24', '2013-12-06 23:01:00', '2013-12-06 23:01:00', 'I believe most people would choose Freemium over Trial. I personally like the idea of having something Freemium that would force power users  to upgrade in 3-4 months. I think that the best of both worlds is what BaseCamp is doing: 3 member freemium and all the other plans have a trial.\n\n\nIt all depends on the audience. I personally prefer that the customer feels:\n- ''Oh, I''ve used this software quite a lot without paying a dime. I know need to expand my operations so I don''t mind paying a little more''\nrather than\n-''Dar-nit, the trial is over... now I need to start paying! Ok, then''\n\n\nOf course, all of this depends on your customers and your product. Large companies like Dropbox and Evernote spend years in that process, and know that they would only get Premium-tier clients if the word gets around by a multitude of Free-tier clients.', 0, '1', 'Disqus/1.1(2.77):1153479511', '', 207, 0),
(213, 1204, 'Mike Ziarko', 'mikeziarko@gmail.com', '', '12.249.99.122', '2013-12-07 15:49:00', '2013-12-07 15:49:00', 'Damian, why not go with the hybrid model as Omar suggests? Have a limited freemium plan alongside several other free trial plans.', 0, '1', 'Disqus/1.1(2.77):1154071220', '', 209, 0),
(214, 1204, 'Damian Thompson', 'damian@linchpin.net', 'http://www.linchpin.net/', '121.54.58.242', '2013-12-07 23:53:00', '2013-12-07 23:53:00', 'You need a HUGE addressable market to make Freemium work (think iOS game apps or dropbox) as it is almost impossible to convert free to paid. You are better off solving a real problem and charging money for it more than not. Remember that free customers cost you money (in support, network fees, etc.) also.', 0, '1', 'Disqus/1.1(2.77):1154468508', '', 213, 0),
(215, 1204, 'Reuben', 'reubens@mimiran.com', 'http://www.mimiran.com/', '99.64.98.25', '2013-12-08 16:05:00', '2013-12-08 16:05:00', 'Great question. The answer depends on a number of factors, including whether you have the resources to support a huge number of non-paying users. In addition, consider if the audience should pay. For example, people have different expectations of Google as a search user or Google as an advertiser. Google may offer a free credit to get started with advertising, but you are going to pay for that eventually. In other situations, non-paying users are useful if they can create a network effect or you have other ways to monetize them. Don''t count on a large percentage of them upgrading to paid plans. Some will hit usage triggers and upgrade, but many are there simply for the "free". There''s a huge change in demand between free and non-free. As a general rule of thumb, B2B apps are more likely to be free trial and B2C apps are more likely to be freemium.', 0, '1', 'Disqus/1.1(2.77):1154981451', '', 207, 0),
