(734, 4398, 'Jaina', 'jaina.mistry84@gmail.com', '', '37.131.1.155', '2014-09-17 12:03:00', '2014-09-17 19:03:00', 'Just like you have mentioned, working remotely has its positives and negatives. I''ve been working remotely for going on 4 months now. And while I do miss the office environment and even part of the every day drudgery of going to work, the flexibility of working from home is freeing. Though at the same time, you have to be very disciplined. It''s incredibly easy to just say, I''ll work from the sofa today in front of the TV. I''d hardly get any work done if I worked that way. \n\n\nI moved to Bahrain 4 months ago, from the UK. My company were very generous in allowing me to move and work for them remotely. So few companies would offer that these days, I feel. So feel very chuffed that they did let me. Work the same UK hours, which is actually better for me here. It''s been an adjustment, that''s for sure, but worth it.', 0, '1', '', '', 0, 0),
(735, 4398, 'alan jones', 'alan@thenewagency.com.au', 'http://about.me/alanjones', '59.167.65.89', '2014-09-17 20:02:00', '2014-09-18 03:02:00', '"plant" or "planet"? either way, I wholeheartedly agree with your point. In fact, I''d argue we''re approaching a time when we stop defining not just companies but whole nations in geographic terms. Why must we be forced to share a tax base and a government with people we share nothing in common with other than locality? Why can''t I pay my taxes and have direct representation in a government-in-the-cloud that then negotiates on my behalf with the nearest providers of healthcare, education, roads, etc?', 0, '1', '', '', 0, 0),
