(1042, 5413, 'eko', 'awoo2xl@yahoo.com', '', '64.202.161.57', '2015-02-12 16:54:00', '2015-02-12 16:54:00', 'I like Ikea''s approach. I think the era of folks getting "freaked out" about answering some of those questions in order for them to receive relevant content because they''re personal might be phasing out. A lot of it is conventional thinking (too creepy), which deter some marketers from taking this brilliant approach. Once someone has taken an interest in receiving promotional emails from you, they''ve already shown some trust/interest in what you''re selling so it only makes sense to capitalize on that in their interest. Posing the "why not ask?" question is a clever way to enlighten them a bit. Good post Jimmy!', 0, '1', 'Disqus/1.1(2.83):1849980134', '', 1037, 0),
(1043, 5413, 'Jimmy Daly', 'runjimdaly@gmail.com', 'http://blog.getvero.com', '107.2.12.250', '2015-02-12 17:06:00', '2015-02-12 17:06:00', 'Here is the real challenge in my mind - convincing new subscribers that supplying this information actually benefits them. The marketer smart enough to make that value proposition is gonna kill it.', 0, '1', 'Disqus/1.1(2.83):1850007587', '', 1042, 0),
(1044, 5432, 'Sujan Patel', 'sujitsu@gmail.com', 'http://wheniwork.com/', '50.244.213.249', '2015-02-12 17:53:00', '2015-02-12 17:53:00', 'Great results Jimmy. I wouldn''t call "The Principal-Agent Problem in Marketing" or other low traffic failures due to lack of action in the post or anything content related. It''s likely the topic or blog post title that caused the low traffic.', 0, '1', 'Disqus/1.1(2.83):1850105965', '', 0, 0),
