(1124, 5652, 'Michael Karp', 'michael@copytactics.com', '', '132.241.174.161', '2015-03-10 20:19:00', '2015-03-10 20:19:00', 'Nice work again Jimmy. \n\n\nEmail frequency is the one that stuck out in my head the most. Totally makes sense now that the answer depends largely on what your subscribers expect from you.\n\n\nI also love your point about building trust. I''m sure it can be tempting for people to send more emails or less emails per week, but if they''ve already built up that expectation from their subscribers, the damage to that trust could end up backfiring. \n\n\nPersonally, now I need to consider whether I want to build an expectation with my subscribers and get the trust benefits from that, or leave my email frequency open-ended by not explicitly saying how often I''m going to email them.\n\n\nEither way, nice read.', 0, '1', 'Disqus/1.1(2.83):1899713176', '', 0, 0),
(1125, 5652, 'Jimmy Daly', 'runjimdaly@gmail.com', 'http://blog.getvero.com', '107.2.46.188', '2015-03-10 20:22:00', '2015-03-10 20:22:00', 'Awesome, glad you found it useful.\n\nI tend to like setting an expectation and sticking to it as it''s the fastest way to build a reliance on your emails. (Product Hunt kills this: http://blog.getvero.com/product-hunt/)\n\n\n\nBut, as with all things email, it really depends on you, your businesses and your audience. There are almost no hard and fast answers.', 0, '1', 'Disqus/1.1(2.83):1899722221', '', 1124, 0),
