(79, 3, '2014-07-05 06:51:36', '2014-07-05 06:51:36', '<p>HTML templates let you upload detailed and complex email templates that you can re-use in your campaigns. This is useful as you can define a static header or footer and only edit the sections you need to for each email.</p>\r\n\r\n<div class="video"><iframe width="810" height="506" src="https://fast.wistia.net/embed/iframe/mc4nmsdcf7" allowtransparency="true" frameborder="0" scrolling="no" class="wistia_embed" name="wistia_embed" allowfullscreen="allowfullscreen" mozallowfullscreen="mozallowfullscreen" webkitallowfullscreen="webkitallowfullscreen" oallowfullscreen="" msallowfullscreen=""></iframe></div>\r\n<h3>Defining editable sections of a template</h3>\r\n<p>In order to define which areas of a template are editable when creating a new campaign you simply add the HTML class ''vero-editable'' to the element you want to edit.</p>\r\n<p>In the example below we are marking the element containgin "Email Marketing Tips" with ''vero-editable''. That means this area<span>will not be static</span>and is expected to be updated whenever you use this template as part of a new campaign.<img src="https://www.getvero.com/assets/docs/html-emails/vero-editable-296c0409e50fe005d1424d5923b716ff.png" alt="Vero-editable" /></p>\r\n\r\n<h3>Uploading a template</h3>\r\n<p>Uploading a template is as easy as visiting the<a href="https://app.getvero.com/templates" target="_blank">HTML templates</a>menu and clicking ''Upload template'':<img src="https://www.getvero.com/assets/docs/html-emails/upload-template-30b14394e8d028021732c2ef9a53f9f5.png" alt="Upload-template" /></p>\r\n<p>You can name your template when you upload it to Vero.</p>\r\n\r\n<h3>Using a template</h3>\r\n<p>When creating a campaign you can choose whether you want to use<em>rich text</em>(i.e. the basic WYSIWYG editor) or whether you''d like to customize one of the templates you''ve uploaded.</p>\r\n<p>To do this simply select<em>HTML template from the two options available in the content section:</em><img src="https://www.getvero.com/assets/docs/html-emails/select-template-4d9ea357bff79a9ac2338631c12f5f54.png" alt="Select-template" /></p>\r\n<p><span>Note:</span>This option only shows up once you have uploaded at least one template.</p>\r\n<p>After you''ve select a template you need to select<em>Update template contents</em>at the bottom of the email editor.</p>\r\n<p>This will take you to a full-screen template editor that allows you to<span>customize your template for this particular email campaign.</span></p>\r\n<p>You can make changes to the areas you marked as<em>editable</em>in the paragraphs above. As you edit, changes appear live in the template preview window so you can see what your template looks like.<img src="https://www.getvero.com/assets/docs/html-emails/edit-btn-e156769efdd573d11fc2b5fc7177df7f.png" alt="Edit-btn" /></p>\r\n<p>Once you are happy with your changes, hit<em>Save changes</em>at the top right. This will take you back to the campaign editor so you can do a final review of your subject line, targeting and so on.</p>\r\n<p>If everything checks out, select<em>Save email</em>to save a draft and head back to the campaign snapshot. On the campaign snapshot You must complete this step otherwise we will use the basic HTML template content you used when you uploaded the HTML template.</p>\r\n\r\n<h3>Updating a base template</h3>\r\n<p>Whenever you use a template for a campaign, a new copy of that template is created based on the changes you make in the full-page WYIWYG editor. If you want to change part of the underlying template, e.g. a logo in the top left corner, you can do this by editing the template being used under the template menu.</p>\r\n<p>Vero will automatically work to update each template where it is certain there are no conflicts. In situations where you change the<span>structure</span>of an underlying template by adding more<em>vero-editable tags</em>Vero will ask you to confirm your changes by editing each campaign that uses the template.<img src="https://www.getvero.com/assets/docs/html-emails/update-template-59c38d78b2afd401b5cf337193a48ad2.png" alt="Update-template" /></p>\r\n<p><span>Note:</span>In this instance the campaign will use the old template until you update the changes.</p>', 'HTML Templates', '', 'publish', 'closed', 'closed', '', 'html-email-templates', '', '', '2014-07-05 06:51:57', '2014-07-05 06:51:57', '', 0, 'http://localhost:8888/?post_type=help_docs&#038;p=79', 0, 'help_docs', '', 0),
(80, 3, '2014-07-05 06:52:57', '2014-07-05 06:52:57', '<p>In Vero you can track both<span>user properties</span>and<span>event properties.</span></p>\r\n<p>A<em>user property</em>is a data point associated with a customer profile. A typical example of a user property is<em>first name.</em>Another example is<em>age.</em></p>\r\n<p>An<em>event property</em>is a data point associated with an individual customer action. Imagine you were tracking the action<em>Viewed product.</em>An example of an event property related to this action would be<em>product name.</em>Another example is<em>product URL.</em></p>\r\n\r\n<h3>User properties</h3>\r\n<p>The great thing about<em>user properties</em>is that you can capture as much data as you want about each individual customer. The names of each property are<span>completely up to you</span>which means you can make them very specific to your business.</p>\r\n<p>As an example we''re going to track some user properties using Vero''s Javascript snippet. Here is an example of the user identify snippet capturing multiple user properties about a customer. In this case we''re capturing their first name and their last name.</p>\r\n\r\n<pre><code class="rainbow" data-language="javascript"><span class="keyword operator">&lt;</span>script type<span class="keyword operator">=</span><span class="string">"text/javascript"</span><span class="keyword operator">&gt;</span>\r\n  _veroq.<span class="support method">push</span>([<span class="string">''user''</span>, {\r\n    <span class="comment">// Required attributes</span>\r\n    id: <span class="string">''1''</span>, <span class="comment">// This ID must be unique per customer</span>\r\n    email: <span class="string">''email@domain.com''</span>, <span class="comment">// For testing, use an email you own.</span>\r\n    <span class="comment">// Include as many optional attributes as you want</span>\r\n    first_name: <span class="string">''Chris''</span>,\r\n    last_name: <span class="string">''Hexton''</span>\r\n  }]);\r\n<span class="keyword operator">&lt;</span>/script<span class="keyword operator">&gt;</span></code></pre>\r\n<div class="highlight"><h5>DID YOU KNOW?</h5>\r\n<p>The<em>email</em>and<em>ID</em>properties are required. These tell Vero who is currently on your site. To learn more, check out the video and documentation on how to<a href="https://www.getvero.com/docs">install Vero</a>in step one.</p></div>\r\n<p>This data will show up on the customer''s profile in Vero. To find their profile, visit the<em>Customers</em>tab and search for their email (or select them from the list).<img src="https://www.getvero.com/assets/docs/dynamic-variables/profile-cb7f7f67860a75f792e74fd38d698b1b.png" alt="Profile" /></p>\r\n<p>This same data is then available for you to use in order to personalize your emails. If you''re creating or editing a campaign, you can insert user properties with the following syntax.</p>\r\n\r\n<pre><code class="rainbow" data-language="generic"><span class="keyword operator">&lt;</span>p<span class="keyword operator">&gt;</span>{{user.first_name}}<span class="keyword operator">&lt;</span>/p<span class="keyword operator">&gt;</span></code></pre>\r\n<p>Make sure you use the<span>exact</span>name of the variable you want to insert (e.g. first_name).</p>\r\n\r\n<div class="highlight"><h5>DID YOU KNOW?</h5>\r\n<p>Vero replaces spaces with underscores for<em>user properties.</em>As mentioned in our guide on<a href="https://www.getvero.com/docs/docs/create-an-email-campaign">creating an email</a>, Vero''s emails use Liquid templating. Underscores are used to ensure you can actually insert the variables (Liquid doesn''t allow spaces.)</p></div>\r\n<p>Here''s how this looks when writing your email:<img src="https://www.getvero.com/assets/docs/dynamic-variables/user-property-00f8269e62ff9a04516fbf111daa2eeb.png" alt="User-property" /></p>\r\n<p>We''ve created a handy shortcut bar on the right of the email WYSIWYG eidotr that makes it easy to click and insert the correct variables at any time.<img src="https://www.getvero.com/assets/docs/dynamic-variables/var-helper-8d9c40f0c7b5c17749f75e2d651b0ac5.png" alt="Var-helper" /></p>\r\n<p>You can learn more about tracking customers and their attributes by viewing step one in these help docs, covering how to<a href="https://www.getvero.com/docs">Install the Vero Library</a>.</p>\r\n\r\n<h3>Event properties</h3>\r\n<p>Much like recording user properties against a customer''s profile, you can track individual event properties with<span>each event</span>(customer action) your customers take.</p>\r\n<p>Using our Javascript, here''s an example of how you would track when a customer views a product and the details of that product:</p>\r\n\r\n<pre><code class="rainbow" data-language="javascript"><span class="keyword operator">&lt;</span>script type<span class="keyword operator">=</span><span class="string">"text/javascript"</span><span class="keyword operator">&gt;</span>\r\n  data <span class="keyword operator">=</span> {\r\n    <span class="string">''name''</span>:       <span class="string">''Travel neck rest''</span>,\r\n    <span class="string">''url''</span>:        <span class="string">''http://travelworld.com/products/travel-neck-rest.html''</span>\r\n  }\r\n  _veroq.<span class="support method">push</span>([<span class="string">''track''</span>, <span class="string">''viewed product''</span>, data]);\r\n<span class="keyword operator">&lt;</span>/script<span class="keyword operator">&gt;</span></code></pre>\r\n<p>You can then insert these variables using a dynamic tag like the one below:</p>\r\n\r\n<pre><code class="rainbow" data-language="generic"><span class="keyword operator">&lt;</span>p<span class="keyword operator">&gt;</span>{{event.product_name}}<span class="keyword operator">&lt;</span>/p<span class="keyword operator">&gt;</span></code></pre>\r\n<p>Here is how this looks in practice:<img src="https://www.getvero.com/assets/docs/dynamic-variables/event-property-c4f973a553db29a2451e99e05f1ef595.png" alt="Event-property" /></p>\r\n<p>It''s important to note that you can<span>only use</span>the event properties attached to the<span>trigger event</span>for an automated campaign. In this case the email would need to be triggered by the<em>Viewed product</em>event, as below.<img src="https://www.getvero.com/assets/docs/dynamic-variables/base-event-9020bafe17fcaa8e79e11d90f8521dae.png" alt="Base-event" /></p>\r\n\r\n<div class="highlight"><h5>DID YOU KNOW?</h5>\r\n<p>You can''t use<em>event properties</em>in newsletters as the data is captured on an event. In a newsletter Vero doesn''t know where to get the data from!</p></div>', 'Use personalized data in emails', '', 'publish', 'closed', 'closed', '', 'dynamic-variables', '', '', '2014-07-05 06:53:07', '2014-07-05 06:53:07', '', 0, 'http://localhost:8888/?post_type=help_docs&#038;p=80', 0, 'help_docs', '', 0),
(81, 3, '2014-07-05 06:54:00', '2014-07-05 06:54:00', '<p>When creating new campaigns it is important to preview your emails both in the browser (for quick changes) and in your own email inbox. In this way you can quickly and easily see what your emails will look like to your customers.</p>\r\n\r\n<h3>Preview an automated campaign</h3>\r\n<p>To preview an automated email, ensure you first select the campaign from the<em>Campaigns</em>menu. Once you are on a<em>Campaign Snapshot</em>page select<em>Actions &gt; Preview - via email:</em><img src="https://www.getvero.com/assets/docs/preview/automated-9cdbff668b03583e2921af2f6094912c.png" alt="Automated" /></p>\r\n<p>You will be presented with a modal window that allows you to choose who to send the preview to and which variation to render (if you are running an A/B test). Vero also stores recent preview addresses:<img src="https://www.getvero.com/assets/docs/preview/dialog-d2c2602ab672058cf19b7c49708bc005.png" alt="Dialog" /></p>\r\n\r\n<h3>Preview a newsletter</h3>\r\n<p>To preview a newsletter campaigns, head to the<em>Newsletters</em>menu. Next to the newsletter you want to preview, select<em>Actions &gt; Preview - via email:</em><img src="https://www.getvero.com/assets/docs/preview/newsletter-4c6a3e7ff0d73dcba1a218e9ee9df5b0.png" alt="Newsletter" /></p>\r\n\r\n<h3>Previewing in browser</h3>\r\n<p>When previewing either newsletters or automated campaigns you can choose to preview your email<span>in browser.</span>This can give you a quick glance at your campaign and allow you to rapidly view changes. To do so, simply select<em>Preview - in browser</em>from the dropdowns instead of<em>via email.</em></p>\r\n<p>You can also render an in-browser preview when editing a campaign:<img src="https://www.getvero.com/assets/docs/preview/when-editing-4e961cee589d8427240d646e50d84777.png" alt="When-editing" /></p>\r\n<p>...or whilst using editing a template:<img src="https://www.getvero.com/assets/docs/preview/editing-template-355bde3d2a707574ef0e5dfe9ed0c43c.png" alt="Editing-template" /></p>\r\n\r\n<h3>Custom user data</h3>\r\n<p>When previewing an email you can select a specific customer whose data you''d like to dynamically insert in your preview. You can do this when you are previewing via email or in the browser. This allows you to test different scenarios when using<a href="http://localhost:3000/docs/dynamic-variables">personalized data in email</a>.</p>\r\n<p>Here''s an example of an in-browser preview rendering the specific data for a user,<em>james@getvero.com:</em><img src="https://www.getvero.com/assets/docs/preview/select-user-6060717f79cec943b884afb49ccd3924.png" alt="Select-user" /></p>', 'Previewing campaigns', '', 'publish', 'closed', 'closed', '', 'previewing-campaigns', '', '', '2015-01-29 04:20:13', '2015-01-29 04:20:13', '', 0, 'http://localhost:8888/?post_type=help_docs&#038;p=81', 0, 'help_docs', '', 0),
(82, 3, '2014-07-05 06:58:12', '2014-07-05 06:58:12', '<p>A/B testing gives you the power to test your email marketing hypotheses and<span>optimize your campaigns on an ongoing basis.</span>A/B testing is what separates a basic email marketer from a pro.</p>\r\n<p>Vero gives you tools to A/B test both<em>newsletters</em>and<em>automated</em>campaigns with ease.</p>\r\n\r\n<h3>Setting up an A/B test on an automated campaign</h3>\r\n<p>You can A/B test the<em>from address,</em><em>subject line</em>and<em>email contents</em>(rich text or HTML template) of any campaign.</p>\r\n<p>To add a variation to an email campaign, view the campaign snapshot of a saved campaign and you''ll see the option to<span>Start an A/B test</span>at the top right.<img src="https://www.getvero.com/assets/docs/ab-tests/start-89410f2ce6fe7561fc61f10d03f3e467.png" alt="Start" /></p>\r\n\r\n<div class="highlight"><h5>DID YOU KNOW?</h5>\r\n<p>If you have already started an A/B test you can edit it at any time by returning to the campaign snapshot screen. Instead of seeing<em>Start an A/B test</em>you''ll see a button to<em>Edit A/B test.</em></p></div>\r\n<p>The A/B test editor allows you to quickly and easily add variations to your emails. When you add a variation it is added to<span>all of the emails in your campaign,</span>even if you have multiple emails in your series.</p>\r\n<p>By default each new variation will have the same from address, subject and content as the Control (base) email variation. By adding the variation across the entire series, you are able to A/B test your campaign holistically. If a customer gets<em>Variation A</em>for the first email in the series, Vero will<span>automatically ensure</span>that they get<em>Variation A</em>throughout the rest of the campaign.</p>\r\n<p>This helps you safely A/B test different templates or from addresses consistenly, which is key to a unified user experience.</p>\r\n<p>To make changes to the from address or subject line, simply click the text and it will become editable, like so:<img src="https://www.getvero.com/assets/docs/ab-tests/edit-subject-19a8018bb919d0d3afe809fa1f8f7be6.png" alt="Edit-subject" /></p>\r\n<p>To edit the body of the email click the ''Edit'' button on the right hand side next to a variation.</p>\r\n<p>Once you are happy scroll to the bottom and select<em>Put A/B test live</em>or<em>Update A/B test</em>to get your test going.</p>\r\n\r\n<h3>Setting up an A/B test on a newsletter campaign</h3>\r\n<p>Learn<a href="https://www.getvero.com/docs/docs/newsletter-email-campaigns">how to create a newsletter campaign</a>using the guide in these docs.</p>\r\n<p>Once you have saved a draft of your newsletter you can add variations to it. To do this, edit the campaign again and scroll to the content area. Here you will see the option to "Add a variation":<img src="https://www.getvero.com/assets/docs/ab-tests/newsletter-var-abc7bb2141de84b8f6aae866612c8887.png" alt="Newsletter-var" /></p>\r\n<p>You can then edit the variation the same as you would edit the control. When you are happy, ensure you select<span>Save variation</span>at the bottom of the newsletter. If you do not do this your<span>changes will be lost.</span></p>\r\n<p><span>Note:</span>If you switch between variation tabs and have not saved the changes to a variation, you will lose your changes. Vero will warn you when you try to do this and haven''t saved your variation yet.</p>\r\n\r\n<h3>Negative variations</h3>\r\n<p>A/B tests on automated campaigns also give you the option to create a<span>negative variation.</span></p>\r\n<p>A negative variation allows you to define a percentage of customers that<span>will not</span>receive the email or email series. Vero will still track the conversinos for these customers, i.e. if they take the goal of the campaign, and report on it.</p>\r\n<p>Negative variations are designed to help you assess whether your campaigns are leading to increased conversions, decreased conversions or make no difference at all.</p>\r\n\r\n<div class="did-you-know">\r\n<h5>DID YOU KNOW?</h5>\r\n<p>When viewing the<a href="https://www.getvero.com/docs/reporting">report data</a>for a campaign, a negative variation will show up just like any other variation. Open and click data is not applicable so will be blank. Conversions will still be tracked.</p>\r\n\r\n</div>\r\n<h3>Setting split percentages</h3>\r\n<p>Regardless of whether you''re testing an automated or newsletter campaign you can easily define the split percentages for each campaign. This determines what percentage of customers get each variation.</p>\r\n<p>To define the split percentage edit your A/B test (automated campaigns) or the campaign itself (newsletter campaigns) and scroll to the bottom. You will see an option to define the split percentages of each variation.<img src="https://www.getvero.com/assets/docs/ab-tests/splits-a103d016ef00c45a822bec78133bd65f.png" alt="Splits" /></p>\r\n<p>Save your A/B test for the changes to the split percentages to take effect.</p>', 'A/B Tests', '', 'publish', 'closed', 'closed', '', 'ab-tests', '', '', '2015-01-29 04:35:55', '2015-01-29 04:35:55', '', 0, 'http://localhost:8888/?post_type=help_docs&#038;p=82', 0, 'help_docs', '', 0),
(83, 3, '2014-07-05 06:59:01', '2014-07-05 06:59:01', '<p>To view the results for a campaign select the<em>Actions menu next to an email campaign</em>and choose<em>View Results.</em></p>\r\n\r\n<div class="highlight"><h5>DID YOU KNOW?</h5>\r\n<p>For automated campaigns you can view the results for an entire campaign or for each individual email within a series. The aggregate results give you the total number of sent, opened, clicked and converted emails for that campaign.</p></div>\r\n<h3>Conversion Report</h3>\r\n<p>The default report you see when viewing a campaign''s results is the<em>Conversion Report.</em></p>\r\n<p>This report presents you with a funnel-like breakdown of the success of your campaign. The focus is always on conversions so this visual lets you quickly and easily see the ultimate success of a campaign:<img src="https://www.getvero.com/assets/docs/reporting/conversions-790e0b53175bebd665cdbf9e62fc8e7b.png" alt="Conversions" /></p>\r\n\r\n<h3>Statistics Report</h3>\r\n<p>To view the<em>Statistics Report</em>select the<em>Reports</em>option at the top right of a<em>View Results</em>page and select it.<img src="https://www.getvero.com/assets/docs/reporting/select-report-08bc528db24345c9ff62fb1fbb58bc21.png" alt="Select-report" /></p>\r\n<p>The statistics report gives you a day-by-day breakdown of your campaign''s results based on the time period selected. We also provide a graph to help you see trends over time, particularly useful for tracking the results of an automated campaign based on changes you''ve made.<img src="https://www.getvero.com/assets/docs/reporting/statistics-c5128a227a291d2745d3eb830657878d.png" alt="Statistics" /></p>', 'Campaign Reporting', '', 'publish', 'closed', 'closed', '', 'reporting', '', '', '2014-07-05 06:59:07', '2014-07-05 06:59:07', '', 0, 'http://localhost:8888/?post_type=help_docs&#038;p=83', 0, 'help_docs', '', 0),
