(2012, 3, '2015-05-10 11:56:48', '2015-05-10 11:56:48', '<table>\n<tbody>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<h3 id="basics">Basics</h3>\nThe Vero API only has two key models: users and actions.\nThe API is designed to be easy to use and understand. The examples included on this page can actually be run. They will work with your <em>Staging</em> project in Vero, ensuring no emails are sent to your customers.</td>\n<td></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<h3 id="authentication">Authentication</h3>\nYou authenticate to the Vero API by providing your authorization token in the request. You can manage your API keys and authorization token in your <a href="https://app.getvero.com/account/api-keys" target="_blank">Vero account</a>. Your authorization token carries privileges so be sure to keep them it secret.To use your authorization token, you need to include it in every request using cURL.\nAll API requests <strong>must</strong> be made over HTTPS.</td>\n<td>\n<h3>&nbsp;</h3>\n<p></p>When using Javascript, you are best to include the following snippet just before the <strong>&lt;/head&gt;</strong> tag on every page of your website.\n<pre class="theme:monokai font-size:14 line-height:18 width-set:true width:100 width-unit:1 top-margin:20 bottom-margin:20 toolbar:2 striped:false nums:false nums-toggle:false wrap:true wrap-toggle:false show-plain:3 tab-size:2 lang:js decode:true">&lt;script type=''text/javascript''&gt;   \n  var _veroq = _veroq || [];   \n  _veroq.push([''init'', {api_key: "YOUR_API_KEY"}]);     \n  (function(){var ve = document.createElement(''script'');ve.type = ''text/javascript'';ve.async = true;ve.src = ''//d3qxef4rp70elm.cloudfront.net/m.js'';var s = document.getElementsByTagName(''script'')[0]; s.parentNode.insertBefore(ve, s);})(); \n&lt;/script&gt;</pre>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<h3 id="users">Users</h3>\nThe Users end-point has two key functions. The first, and primary, is <strong>identify</strong>.\nThis end-point allows you to add or update a user (subscriber) to your Vero database. You must record an identifier (ID) to add a user to your database and you must also record an email in order to actually email that customer.\nYou are also able to store additional user attributes for use in your various email campaigns. These are typically values like first_name, last_name, age, etc.\nAll fields except the identifier may be updated using this end-point.\nThe second end-point is <strong>reidentify</strong>. This end-point gives you the ability to alias a user to a new ID. To do so, you pass on the customer''s current ID and the ID you want to replace.</td>\n<td>\n<h3>&nbsp;</h3>\nThe following snippet allows you to <strong>add </strong>or <strong>update</strong> subscribers and their attributes in your Vero database. In this example we update a user with the <em>identifier</em> (a Vero system field) <em>1234 </em>and email address <em>john@smith.com</em> and store the properties <em>first_name</em> and <em>last_name</em> with values <em>John </em>and<em> Smith</em> respectively.\n<pre class="theme:monokai font-size:14 line-height:18 width-set:true width:100 width-unit:1 top-margin:20 bottom-margin:20 toolbar:2 striped:false nums:false nums-toggle:false wrap:true wrap-toggle:false show-plain:3 tab-size:2 lang:js decode:true">&lt;script&gt;  \n  _veroq.push([''user'', {      \n    id: ''CUSTOMER_ID'', // ID must be unique    \n    email: ''CUSTOMER_EMAIL'', // Replace each variable dynamically based on the logged-in user  \n    first_name: ''CUSTOMER_NAME'',    \n    last_name: ''CUSTOMER_LAST_NAME''  \n  }]);\n&lt;/script&gt;</pre>\n<strong>Note</strong> that if a user profile with <em>identifier</em> 1234 already existed, this would simply update the <em>email, first_name</em> and <em>last_name</em> fields of that user. If the profile did not exist, it would be created on the fly.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<h3 id="actions">Actions</h3>\nThe Actions end-point has a single function: it allows you to track when an individual user takes a specific action on your website.\nFor example, you may want to record when a customer clicks a certain button or uses a certain feature.\nTo use this end-point, you are required to record the identifier (ID) of the user taking the action, the name of the action you want to record and (optionally) attributes associated with that action. In the example provided, you are tracking when a customer views a product and are also capturing the attributes name, price and a link to the product image.\nYou can use these attributes to create more targeted segments and more granular emails in Vero. <strong>Note</strong> that there are two reserved action names: <em>Identified</em> and <em>Visited site</em>. You should not use these action names as they are tracked automatically by Vero when a customer is first added to the database and when they are again seen on your website.</td>\n<td>\n<h3>&nbsp;</h3>\nThe following snippet <strong>tracks an action</strong> called <em>Viewed product</em> for the user with <em>identifier</em> 1234. It also includes optional attributes including the product name and URL.\n<pre class="theme:monokai font-size:14 line-height:18 width-set:true width:100 width-unit:1 top-margin:20 bottom-margin:20 toolbar:2 striped:false nums:false nums-toggle:false wrap:true wrap-toggle:false show-plain:3 tab-size:2 lang:js decode:true">&lt;script&gt;  \n  _veroq.push([''track'', ''viewed product'', {      \n    product_name: ''Red T-shirt'',    \n    product_url: ''http://www.yourdomain.com/products/red-t-shirt''  \n  }])\n;&lt;/script&gt;</pre>\n<strong>Note</strong> that you must call this code on a page where a user has been identified and has a stored cookie. Refer to <strong>Users</strong> above for more detail.</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<h3 id="tags">Tags</h3>\nAlong with attributes, you can record tags on users. A user profile in Vero may have many tags. For example you might tag a customer with the tag "VIP".\nTags are also useful as they can be added via the API, CSV and the Vero API.\nThe Tags end-point has two functions: to add or remove tags. To add a tag (or series of tags), simply include an array of the tags you''d like to add. You must also provide the identifier (ID) of the user you want to update.<strong>Note</strong> that you can add and remove tags in the same API call.</td>\n<td>\n<h3>&nbsp;</h3>\nThe following snippet <strong>adds</strong> the tag <em>warm-lead</em> and <strong>removes</strong> the tag <em>prospect</em> from the user with <em>identifier</em> 1234.\n<pre class="theme:monokai font-size:14 line-height:18 width-set:true width:100 width-unit:1 top-margin:20 bottom-margin:20 toolbar:2 striped:false nums:false nums-toggle:false wrap:true wrap-toggle:false show-plain:3 tab-size:2 lang:js decode:true">&lt;script&gt;  \n  _veroq.push([''tags'', {    \n    id: 1234,    \n    add: [''warm_lead''],    \n    remove: [''prospect'']  \n  }])\n;&lt;/script&gt;</pre>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<h3 id="unsubscribes">Unsubscribes</h3>\nThe unsubscribe API gives you a simple way to unsubscribe a user.\nTo unsubscribe a user, simply pass up the identifier (ID) of the user you want to unsubscribe.</td>\n<td>\n<h3>&nbsp;</h3>\nThe following snippet <b>unsubscribes </b>the user with <em>identifier</em> 1234.\n<pre class="theme:monokai font-size:14 line-height:18 width-set:true width:100 width-unit:1 top-margin:20 bottom-margin:20 toolbar:2 striped:false nums:false nums-toggle:false wrap:true wrap-toggle:false show-plain:3 tab-size:2 lang:js decode:true">&lt;script&gt;  \n  _veroq.push([''unsubscribe'', {    \n    id: 1234  \n  }]);\n&lt;/script&gt;</pre>\n</td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td>\n<h3 id="heartbeat">Heartbeat</h3>\nDue to many customer''s requirements for mission-critical up-time, the Heartbeat input indicates the state of the Vero API.\nA successful response will result in the following JSON response with a 200 status code.\nAlternatively, if the API is unreachable or is experiencing a major issue, you will get the following JSON response with a 503 status code.\nThis API is available to be pinged on an regular basis for mission critical operations. It provides you with a programatic means of checking the status of our API. Additionally we have our own monitoring software constantly pinging this endpoint for issues.</td>\n<td></td>\n</tr>\n<tr>\n<td></td>\n<td></td>\n</tr>\n</tbody>\n</table>', 'Javascript', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '109-autosave-v1', '', '', '2015-05-10 11:56:48', '2015-05-10 11:56:48', '', 109, 'http://localhost:8888/109-autosave-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
