(2134, 3, '2015-02-06 06:31:50', '2015-02-06 06:31:50', 'The best way to get data into Vero is using our API. Our API tracks contacts and their actions.\n\nIf you are coming from an email service provider such as Mailchimp, you will be familiar with the concept of HTML-based email forms.\n\nThese forms allow you to collect a subscriber''s email address, name and other (custom) details easily using a little HTML on your website.\n\nVero also supports email forms, with one key difference. Traditionally, when a contact fills out an email form they are added to a <strong>list</strong>. In Vero, rather than being added to a list, a contact that fills out a web form <strong>triggers an action</strong>. That action could be as simple as <strong>Subscribes to blog</strong>.\n\nYou can then use this action to create a segment or automate a behavioral email: so you get twice the power from a single web form!\n\nTo generate a form, head to `Configuration &gt; HTML Forms` and you''ll be shown Vero''s point-and-click interface to create a form:\n\nSCREENSHOT\n\nVero forms <strong>always</strong>collect the contact''s `email` but you can collect any fields you want. We will show you fields you''ve collected in the past on the left hand side.\n\nYou <strong>must</strong>define the action that will be triggered when the contact fills out this particular form.\n\nThe final part of our form builder allows you to define what your contacts see after completing the form:\n\nSCREENSHOT\n\nBy default, we''ll show them a confirmation screen that looks like this:\n\nSCREENSHOT\n\nYou can define a screen if they fail to complete the form successfully (i.e. enter an invalid email) or when they do complete the form successfully. Generally this would be a custom <strong>Thanks for subscribing</strong>page.', 'Create a HTML email subscribe form', '', 'publish', 'closed', 'closed', '', 'create-a-html-email-subscribe-form', '', '', '2015-02-06 06:31:50', '2015-02-06 06:31:50', '', 0, 'http://www.getvero.com/?post_type=help_docs&amp;p=2134', 0, 'help_docs', '', 0),
(2135, 3, '2015-02-06 06:33:18', '2015-02-06 06:33:18', 'Highlight: the libraries mentioned here work well, but many customers now choose to use <a href="http://www.segment.com">Segment</a> which allows you to install one library and track data to multiple tools, including Vero, KISSmetrics and Mixpanel.\n\nMost customers of Vero use an analytics tool to make solid decisions when it comes to their website and what email marketing campaigns they can automate.\n\nIf you use KISSmetrics'' or Mixpanel''s <strong>Javascript API library</strong> then you can use one of Vero''s custom wrappers.\n\nRather than re-installing all of the Javsacript required to track your contacts'' actions on your website using Vero''s library, our integrations let you change one piece of code in `&lt;/head&gt;` of your website, and all of the contacts you `identify` and actions you `track` in either KISSmetrics or Mixpanel will also be sent to Vero.\n\nHighlight: Vero''s integrations <strong>only</strong> work with the KISSmetrics and Mixpanel Javascript APIs, not their backend Ruby, Python, PHP or other libraries.\n\nTo find the right code to copy and paste onto your website, head to the integration pages for our <a href="https://github.com/getvero/vero-api/blob/master/sections/kissmetrics.md">KISSmetrics</a> and <a href="https://github.com/getvero/vero-api/blob/master/sections/mixpanel.md">Mixpanel</a> integrations on Github.', 'Integrate Vero with KISSmetrics or Mixpanel', '', 'publish', 'closed', 'closed', '', 'integrate-vero-with-kissmetrics-or-mixpanel', '', '', '2015-02-06 06:33:18', '2015-02-06 06:33:18', '', 0, 'http://www.getvero.com/?post_type=help_docs&amp;p=2135', 0, 'help_docs', '', 0),
(2136, 3, '2015-02-06 06:33:46', '2015-02-06 06:33:46', '[help_highlight_no_heading text="This only applies to customers using our Vero Javascript API Library or Segment.com''s Javascript library."]\n\nBy default, Vero''s Javascript wrapper <strong>does not</strong>track pageviews. Tracing pageviews can quickly become overwhelming, as most customers find they get better value when defining custom events in Vero.\n\nIt''s easy to turn pageview tracking on however, and use pageviews when defining your segments.\n\nSimply add the following line to the Vero Javascript library just before the `&lt;/head&gt;` tag in our HTML template:\n<pre class="theme:github bottom-set:false toolbar:2 marking:false nums-toggle:false plain:false plain-toggle:false copy:false popup:false lang:default decode:true">&lt;script&gt;\n    _veroq.push([''trackPageview'']);\n&lt;/script&gt;</pre>\nOnce installed correctly you will start seeing *Viewed page* in the Logs section of your Vero dashboard. Each pageview captures the URL of the page visited and you can use this to segment your contacts.\n\nSCREENSHOT\n\nThis should go<strong>below</strong>the main Vero Javascript Library code: you can get a full copy of the Vero Javascript Library code from our <a href="http://www.getvero.com/api">API Reference Documentation.</a>', 'How to track pageviews with Vero''s API', '', 'publish', 'closed', 'closed', '', 'how-to-track-pageviews-with-veros-api', '', '', '2015-02-06 06:33:46', '2015-02-06 06:33:46', '', 0, 'http://www.getvero.com/?post_type=help_docs&amp;p=2136', 0, 'help_docs', '', 0),
(2137, 3, '2015-02-06 06:36:52', '2015-02-06 06:36:52', 'Highlight: This only applies to customers using our Vero Javascript API Library. Our backend libraries do not use cookies.\n\nWhen using Vero''s Javascript API, you call the `identify` method whenever you get a contact''s permission to email them (logged in users, customers that complete checkout or an explicit subscribe form).\n\nOftentimes, visitors won''t enter their email every time they return to your website.\n\nWhen you call `_veroq.push([''user'', {email: ''tyrion.lannister@casterlyrock.co''}]);`, Vero adds a new contact to your Vero database and drops a cookie that identifies this contact on your website.\n\nThis means that if the contact returns and does not enter their email, Vero is still able to track which pages they visit and actions they take.\n\nThe cookie has an infinite expiration date. If a contact was to browse your website on another device (an iPad when they had previously used their laptop) then Vero would lose sight of that contact until they enter their email again. At that time, Vero will be able to see the user on both devices.\n\n<strong>Advanced</strong>\n\nIf you want, you can append the following to any link in an outgoing email: `?user_id={{user.id}}`.\n\nVero will replace this with a unique reference identifying the customer.\n\nIf the customer clicks through to your website (or any page on which you have Vero''s main Javascript Library installed) the customer will be immediately identified via Vero, without you having to explicitly call `_veroq.push([''user'', {}]);`.\n\nIn this way you can track users as they move between devices, or as you direct them to new landing pages.', 'How Vero cookies contacts on your website using Javascript', '', 'publish', 'closed', 'closed', '', 'how-vero-cookies-contacts-on-your-website-using-javascript', '', '', '2015-02-06 06:36:52', '2015-02-06 06:36:52', '', 0, 'http://www.getvero.com/?post_type=help_docs&amp;p=2137', 0, 'help_docs', '', 0),
(2138, 3, '2015-02-06 06:37:24', '2015-02-06 06:37:24', 'By default, Vero will cookie a customer on the current unique domain. If a customer was on `blog.getvero.com`, they would be cookied solely on this domain.\n\nYou can tell Vero to cookie the user at the root domain. To do so, add the following line of code just before the `` tag on your website:\n<pre class="theme:github bottom-set:false toolbar:2 marking:false nums-toggle:false plain:false plain-toggle:false copy:false popup:false lang:default decode:true ">&lt;script&gt;\n    _veroq.push([''domain'', ''getvero.com'']);\n&lt;/script&gt;</pre>\nThis will ensure the cookie is stored at the root domain level. If you apply this code on all of your subdomians, your contacts will be tracked across all subdomains, from one to the other.', 'Tracking contacts across subdomains', '', 'publish', 'closed', 'closed', '', 'tracking-contacts-across-subdomains', '', '', '2015-02-06 06:37:24', '2015-02-06 06:37:24', '', 0, 'http://www.getvero.com/?post_type=help_docs&amp;p=2138', 0, 'help_docs', '', 0),
(2139, 3, '2015-02-06 06:37:43', '2015-02-06 06:37:43', '[help_highlight_no_heading text="This only applies to customers using our Vero Javascript API Library or Segment.com''s Javascript library."]\n\nSometimes you will track and cookie a contact using a random identifier, or their email address, and later you will want to update this value with a unique identifier from your own database or system.\n\nFor example, if you had called the `identify` method and tracked a contact with the email `tyrion.lannister@casterlyrock.com` as a subscriber on your blog but, after they signed up for your free trial, wanted to identify them with your database identifier of `1285`, you can use Vero''s `re-identify` method to update the contact''s profile.\n\nTo learn about the re-identify (or alias) method in detail, refer to our <a href="http://www.getvero.com/api">API Reference Documentation</a>.\n\nAn example of the re-identify method is below:\n<pre class="theme:github bottom-set:false toolbar:2 marking:false nums-toggle:false plain:false plain-toggle:false copy:false popup:false lang:default decode:true ">&lt;script&gt;\n    _veroq.push([''reidentify'', ''1285'']);\n&lt;/script&gt;</pre>Segment''s `alias` method works in the same way. Vero is the only email marketing platform that works with Segment and provides an `alias` method, giving you a lot of power and flexibility over how your contacts are tracked.', 'Change the email or ID of a customer using ''alias''', '', 'publish', 'closed', 'closed', '', 'change-the-email-or-id-of-a-customer-using-alias', '', '', '2015-02-06 06:37:43', '2015-02-06 06:37:43', '', 0, 'http://www.getvero.com/?post_type=help_docs&amp;p=2139', 0, 'help_docs', '', 0),
(2145, 24, '2015-02-08 01:23:47', '2015-02-08 01:23:47', 'Vero will send you an email when you cross the subscriber or email thresholds over a 30-day period. You will automatically be upgraded to the appropriate plan.\n\nYou can downgrade at any time and, if your usage fluctuates, can minimize your spend each and every month.\n\nYou can manage your subscriptions in the Vero Dashboard under Account -&gt; Billing -&gt; Subscription', 'What happens if you exceed your subscription limits?', '', 'publish', 'closed', 'closed', '', 'what-happens-if-you-exceed-your-subscription-limits', '', '', '2015-02-08 01:23:47', '2015-02-08 01:23:47', '', 0, 'http://www.getvero.com/?post_type=help_docs&amp;p=2145', 0, 'help_docs', '', 0),
(2146, 24, '2015-02-08 01:24:41', '2015-02-08 01:24:41', 'By choosing to pay annually, you get two months of Vero free each year.\n\nPaying annually also means your email limits are spread out across the year. For example, if you are on our $149/month plan and can send up to 175,000 emails per month, on our annual plan you can send up to 2,100,000 emails <b>per year</b>. This means that seasonal spikes in email volume will not require you to go up a plan, saving you even more.', 'What happens if you elect to pay annually?', '', 'publish', 'closed', 'closed', '', 'what-happens-if-you-elect-to-pay-annually', '', '', '2015-02-08 01:24:41', '2015-02-08 01:24:41', '', 0, 'http://www.getvero.com/?post_type=help_docs&amp;p=2146', 0, 'help_docs', '', 0),
(2147, 24, '2015-02-08 01:50:54', '2015-02-08 01:50:54', '[help_highlight_no_heading text="The ability to add team members is available on our $199/month and above plans. To learn more, check out Vero''s Plans and Pricing."]\n\nAdministrator''s of a Vero account can add and remove team members.\n\nThe original user of a Vero account (the user that signed up) is the default administrator.\n\nBy visiting `Configuration &gt; Account &gt; Team` the administrator can invite team members using the ''Invite user'' button:\n\n<a href="http://www.getvero.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/02/Screen-Shot-2015-02-08-at-12.44.08-PM.png"><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-2152" src="https://www.getvero.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/02/Screen-Shot-2015-02-08-at-12.44.08-PM.png" alt="Screen Shot 2015-02-08 at 12.44.08 PM" width="989" height="101" /></a>\n\nOnce invited, the administrator can grant access to each Vero project within your Vero account. There are three levels of access:\n<ul>\n	<li><strong>Administrator</strong> - this is only available on the parent (top level) project within Vero. Administrators have full access to all Vero functions and team management.</li>\n	<li><strong>Edit / View</strong> - this enables the user to both view and edit campaigns.</li>\n	<li><strong>View only</strong> - this allows users to view logs, campaign statistic reports and copies of email campaigns, but not to make changes or update.</li>\n</ul>\nOnce invited, the new user will received an email from from Vero referencing your account and asking the new user to set a password.\n\n<a href="http://www.getvero.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/02/Screen-Shot-2015-02-08-at-12.48.21-PM.png"><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-2153" src="https://www.getvero.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/02/Screen-Shot-2015-02-08-at-12.48.21-PM.png" alt="Screen Shot 2015-02-08 at 12.48.21 PM" width="926" height="401" /></a>\n\nYou can revoke access for any team member by selecting Remove on the Team management screen.\n\n<a href="http://www.getvero.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/02/Screen-Shot-2015-02-08-at-12.47.38-PM.png"><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-2154" src="https://www.getvero.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/02/Screen-Shot-2015-02-08-at-12.47.38-PM.png" alt="Screen Shot 2015-02-08 at 12.47.38 PM" width="1122" height="166" /></a>', 'How to invite team members to Vero', '', 'publish', 'closed', 'closed', '', 'how-to-invite-team-members-to-vero', '', '', '2015-02-08 01:50:54', '2015-02-08 01:50:54', '', 0, 'http://www.getvero.com/?post_type=help_docs&amp;p=2147', 0, 'help_docs', '', 0),
(2155, 24, '2015-02-08 01:51:46', '2015-02-08 01:51:46', 'The fastest way to get a response from Vero is via email.\n\nOur email support, support@getvero.com, is reviewed 24 hours per day and we aim to provide resolutions within 12 hours. In many cases responses are within an hour.\n\nFor accounts on our $549/month+ plans, Vero also offers phone support at 8am-7pm AEST (GMT+10) and 24/7 phone support for emergency contact.\n\nIf you have any questions, please email support@getvero.com.', 'How Vero handles customer support', '', 'publish', 'closed', 'closed', '', 'how-vero-handles-customer-support', '', '', '2015-02-08 01:51:46', '2015-02-08 01:51:46', '', 0, 'http://www.getvero.com/?post_type=help_docs&amp;p=2155', 0, 'help_docs', '', 0),
(2156, 24, '2015-02-08 02:00:16', '2015-02-08 02:00:16', 'Once your Vero trial is over, you can upgrade to a paid plan by going to `Configuration > Account > Subscriptions.`\n\nSimply select your plan, and whether you prefer monthly or yearly billing:\n\n<a href="http://www.getvero.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/02/Screen-Shot-2015-02-08-at-12.54.20-PM.png"><img src="https://www.getvero.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/02/Screen-Shot-2015-02-08-at-12.54.20-PM.png" alt="Screen Shot 2015-02-08 at 12.54.20 PM" width="1126" height="572" class="alignnone size-full wp-image-2157" /></a>\n[help_highlight_no_heading text="Yearly billing comes with two free months. You can switch to yearly billing at any time."]\n\nEnter your credit card details and select Save. Your account is now updated.\n\nAfter upgrading, you can return the Subscriptions page to see which plan you are currently on, your usage thresholds (email and subscriber limits) and how much of these thresholds you have used.\n\nSCREENSHOT', 'How to upgrade to a paid plan', '', 'publish', 'closed', 'closed', '', 'how-to-upgrade-to-a-paid-plan', '', '', '2015-02-08 02:00:16', '2015-02-08 02:00:16', '', 0, 'http://www.getvero.com/?post_type=help_docs&amp;p=2156', 0, 'help_docs', '', 0),
(2158, 24, '2015-02-08 02:01:34', '2015-02-08 02:01:34', 'If you need to update the credit card on file for your Vero account, visit `Configuration > Account > Credit card.`\n\nUnder this menu you can update your card details by entering your card number, cardholder name and CVC number.\n\nVero will email you when your card is about to expire to remind you to update your credit card details.', 'How to change your credit card', '', 'publish', 'closed', 'closed', '', 'how-to-change-your-credit-card', '', '', '2015-02-08 02:01:34', '2015-02-08 02:01:34', '', 0, 'http://www.getvero.com/?post_type=help_docs&amp;p=2158', 0, 'help_docs', '', 0),
(2159, 24, '2015-02-08 02:02:20', '2015-02-08 02:02:20', 'To cancel your Vero account, email support@getvero.com.\n\nWe will cancel your account at any time - if you''re not happy, we''re not happy.', 'How to cancel a Vero account', '', 'publish', 'closed', 'closed', '', 'how-to-cancel-a-vero-account', '', '', '2015-02-08 02:02:20', '2015-02-08 02:02:20', '', 0, 'http://www.getvero.com/?post_type=help_docs&amp;p=2159', 0, 'help_docs', '', 0),
(2160, 24, '2015-02-08 02:03:54', '2015-02-08 02:03:54', 'To view a copy of your monthly invoices that you can print, select `Configuration > Account > Invoices.` \n\nEach of our invoices can be printed as a PDF document.\n\nYou can also add your physical address and Vero will render this on all past and future invoices.\n\nUnder the Invoices menu you can also toggle monthly billing emails to your email address.', 'How to view your past invoices', '', 'publish', 'closed', 'closed', '', 'how-to-view-your-past-invoices', '', '', '2015-02-08 02:03:54', '2015-02-08 02:03:54', '', 0, 'http://www.getvero.com/?post_type=help_docs&amp;p=2160', 0, 'help_docs', '', 0),
(2161, 24, '2015-02-09 06:09:20', '2015-02-09 06:09:20', 'Vero provides webhooks for the following events within the Vero platform:\n<ul>\n	<li>Sent emails (an email is sent by Vero)</li>\n	<li>Deliveries (an email is delievered and received by the recipient email server)</li>\n	<li>Opens</li>\n	<li>Clicks</li>\n	<li>Bounces (hard and soft)</li>\n	<li>Unsubscribes</li>\n	<li>Spam complaints (where available)</li>\n</ul>\nAll of Vero''s webhooks are sent to a single notification address. To enable the webhooks, go to `Configuration &gt; Account &gt; Webhooks` and enter the URL at which you wish to receive the webhooks.\n\nSCREENSHOT\n\n[help_highlight_no_heading text="For testing, you should check out Request Bin - it''s a fantastic way to see the webhooks Vero (or any service) sends."]\n\nYou can select Test and Vero will send an example of a webhook to the URL you''ve entered. This ensures Vero has registered the URL.\n\nOnce you have entered the URL you can choose which webhook events you want to track.\n\nA copy of the data available with each webhook event is below\n\nGET EXAMPLES OF JSON HASHES FOR WEBHOOKS', 'Setting up Vero''s webhooks', '', 'publish', 'closed', 'closed', '', 'setting-up-veros-webhooks', '', '', '2015-02-09 06:09:20', '2015-02-09 06:09:20', '', 0, 'http://www.getvero.com/?post_type=help_docs&amp;p=2161', 0, 'help_docs', '', 0),
(2162, 24, '2015-02-09 06:09:00', '2015-02-09 06:09:00', '[help_highlight_no_heading text="You can only export files up to 50,000 rows from the Vero UI. If you want to export more data, or data that you can''t see how to export in the UI, please email support@getvero.com and we''ll do our best to do it for you as quickly as possible."]\n\nThere are two ways to export data from Vero:\n\n1. <strong>You can export a list of contacts (and their properties) that belong to any segment.</strong> To do this, visit a segment, select <em>View users</em>and then select <em>Export</em> in the top right of the screen. The output file includes the email address, ID and all other properties of each contact in CSV format.\n\nSCREENSHOT\n\n2. <strong>You can export the results of an email campaign.</strong> To do this, visit the <strong>Reports</strong> menu and filter down to the campaign data you want to export. Select <em>Export</em> in the top right of the screen.\n\nSCREENSHOT\n\nIn both cases, a CSV file will be generated that you can download.', 'How to export customer data', '', 'publish', 'closed', 'closed', '', 'how-to-export-customer-data', '', '', '2015-02-09 06:09:00', '2015-02-09 06:09:00', '', 0, 'http://www.getvero.com/?post_type=help_docs&amp;p=2162', 0, 'help_docs', '', 0),
(2163, 24, '2015-02-09 06:08:26', '2015-02-09 06:08:26', 'Vero tracks what customers do on your website after <strong>opening</strong> or <strong>clicking</strong>one of your email campaigns.\n\nTo define a conversion action, simply select one of the actions you are tracking on your website as part of the campaign creation process. For example, as part of creating a newsletter, you select the conversion action like so:\n\nSCREENSHOT\n\nTo learn more about this process, refer to the article <em>How to create an email campaign</em>.\n\nOnce setup, Vero will start tracking your conversions. Vero tracks:\n\n- <strong>Direct conversion</strong>: these are tracked when a contact clicks on one of your emails, returns to your site and takes an action in the <em>same session</em>. Right now this is only supported for customers using our Javascript snippet.\n- <strong>View-through conversions</strong>: these are tracked when a contact opens a campaign and ultimately returns to your site to complete the conversion action. In this instance, we track the conversion if it is within a <em>conversion window</em>, e.g. 30 days, and assign the conversion to the campaign most recently opened by the contact.\n- <strong>Indirect conversions</strong>: these are tracked when a contact receives a campaign and later takes the conversion action on your website. In this instance, we track the conversion if it is within a <em>conversion window</em>, e.g. 30 days, and assign the conversion to the campaign most recently received by the contact. <strong>Indirect conversions</strong>are useful for use with our negative variations only, so Vero can track the actions of contacts that never even receive a particular campaign.\n\nYou can customise the conversion window used to track view-through conversions under the `Configuration &gt; Account &gt; Advanced` menu item. By default, this is set to 30.', 'How Vero''s conversion tracking works', '', 'publish', 'closed', 'closed', '', 'how-veros-conversion-tracking-works', '', '', '2015-02-09 06:08:26', '2015-02-09 06:08:26', '', 0, 'http://www.getvero.com/?post_type=help_docs&amp;p=2163', 0, 'help_docs', '', 0),
(2164, 24, '2015-02-09 06:08:05', '2015-02-09 06:08:05', 'Vero can automatically append UTM parameters to outbound links in your email campaigns so that you can get a detailed view of your email marketing campaigns'' impact on your Google Analytics results.\n\nSelect `Configuration &gt; Account &gt; Integrations &gt; Google Analytics` and select <em>Enable</em>to automatically append UTM codes to all links in your email campaigns.\n\nVero will append UTM tags in the following manner:\n<ul>\n	<li>`utm_source` is, by default, set to V<em>ero</em>. You can customise this under `Configuration &gt; Account &gt; Integration &gt; Google Analytics`</li>\n	<li>`utm_source` is, by default, set to <em>email</em>. You can customise this under `Configuration &gt; Account &gt; Integration &gt; Google Analytics`</li>\n	<li>`utm_campaign` is populated with the name of your campaign</li>\n	<li>`utm_term` is populated with either <em>Control</em>or the variation of your campaign, e.g. <em>A</em>, <em>B</em>, etc. when running an A/B test.</li>\n</ul>\nIf you <strong>add your own UTM tags</strong>to any link, these will override the Vero defaults. For example, you could input a link as follows:\n\n`http://www.yoursite.com?utm_campaign=some_term`\n\nVero would only append our `utm_source`, `utm_term` and `utm_medium` tags, using your custom `utm_campaign` on this link.', 'How to integrate Vero with Google Analytics for result tracking', '', 'publish', 'closed', 'closed', '', 'how-to-integrate-vero-with-google-analytics-for-result-tracking', '', '', '2015-02-09 06:08:05', '2015-02-09 06:08:05', '', 0, 'http://www.getvero.com/?post_type=help_docs&amp;p=2164', 0, 'help_docs', '', 0),
(2165, 24, '2015-02-09 06:07:20', '2015-02-09 06:07:20', 'Most analytics tools support UTM codes. At this time, this is the best way to integrate Vero with on-site analytics tools such as KISSmetrics or Mixpanel, and it should give you a complete picture of the success of your campaigns.\n\nTo learn how to enable and customise UTM tags on links in your campaigns, refer to the article <em>How to integrate Vero with Google Analytics for result tracking.</em>', 'How to integrate Vero''s reporting with KISSmetrics, Mixpanel and other analytics tools', '', 'publish', 'closed', 'closed', '', 'how-to-integrate-veros-reporting-with-kissmetrics-mixpanel-and-other-analytics-tools', '', '', '2015-02-09 06:07:20', '2015-02-09 06:07:20', '', 0, 'http://www.getvero.com/?post_type=help_docs&amp;p=2165', 0, 'help_docs', '', 0),
(2167, 24, '2015-02-12 10:22:13', '2015-02-12 10:22:13', 'User attributes are things that users <b>have</b>  like <i>first name, last name, age, location, lifetime value</i>  theyre the properties of the individual subscribers in your database. Usually you collect this data when users sign up on your website or fill out surveys and forms. This data is really useful for segmentation, so Vero makes it easy to capture any custom attribute that you want to.\n\nUser actions are things that users <b>do </b> like <i>sign up, check out, view a product page, subscribe to the blog</i> and so on  theyre the things individual subscribers do on your website. Usually you collect this data as customers browse your site and use its features. You can capture as many actions as you want for each customer using our API.', 'What are user attributes and user actions?', '', 'publish', 'closed', 'closed', '', 'what-are-user-attributes-and-user-actions', '', '', '2015-02-12 10:22:13', '2015-02-12 10:22:13', '', 0, 'http://www.getvero.com/?post_type=help_docs&amp;p=2167', 0, 'help_docs', '', 0),
(2175, 3, '2015-02-13 09:40:43', '2015-02-13 09:40:43', '<em>Tags</em> are a power way to enhance segmentation.\n\nMost customers do not use tags regularly, but they can be used in a range of different situations.\n\n[help_highlight_no_heading text="If you''ve used other email marketing tools, note that Vero''s tags typically hold a different meaning."]\n\nThe power of tags is that you can manually add tags to individuals via the Vero UI, automatically add tags via our API or add tags in bulk using a CSV upload.\n\nWhen you create segments, you can filter users based on which tags they have and which they don''t. This can let you create preference lists, emulate static lists or use Vero as a lightweight CRM.', 'What are tags?', '', 'publish', 'closed', 'closed', '', 'what-are-tags', '', '', '2015-02-13 09:40:43', '2015-02-13 09:40:43', '', 0, 'http://veropublic.staging.wpengine.com/?post_type=help_docs&amp;p=2175', 0, 'help_docs', '', 0),
(2177, 3, '2015-02-13 09:44:14', '2015-02-13 09:44:14', '<em>Segments</em> are one of the key features that give Vero its power.\n\nUnlike many of the more traditional email marketing tools, Vero uses segments in the place of lists. Lists are static groups of contacts while segments are dynamic groups created by filtering your Vero database based on your contacts'' properties, actions, past email interactions and tags.\n\nAn example of segmentation in practice is below.\n\nTo create a segment called <strong>Paying customers</strong> you will include any user that has <strong>triggered the event <em>Charges Card</em> at least once.</strong>\n\nThis segment would then automatically include anyone that has previously taken the <em>Charges Card</em> action (which you track via your website). Vero will automatically add contacts to this segment in realtime as they trigger their first <em>Charges Card</em> action.\n\n<a href="http://veropublic.staging.wpengine.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/02/Screen-Shot-2015-02-16-at-3.47.22-PM.png"><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-2204" src="http://veropublic.staging.wpengine.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/02/Screen-Shot-2015-02-16-at-3.47.22-PM.png" alt="Screen Shot 2015-02-16 at 3.47.22 PM" width="1098" height="325" /></a>', 'What is a segment?', '', 'publish', 'closed', 'closed', '', 'what-is-a-segment', '', '', '2015-02-13 09:44:14', '2015-02-13 09:44:14', '', 0, 'http://veropublic.staging.wpengine.com/?post_type=help_docs&amp;p=2177', 0, 'help_docs', '', 0),
(2178, 3, '2015-02-13 09:45:22', '2015-02-13 09:45:22', '<em>Projects</em> are their own, isolated environments.\n\nEach project has a separate <strong>contact and campaign databases</strong>, separate <strong>API keys</strong> and separate <strong>campaigns</strong>. In other words, each <em>Project</em> is basically a standalone Vero account.\n\nYou can have up to three projects on our base plan, and many more on our higher plans.\n\n[help_highlight title="A note to agencies" text="If you''re an agency, you may also use projects to manage multiple clients. This is a common use-case for Vero Projects."]\n\nEach project has it''s own <em>Settings</em> as well. The most important of these is the emailing <strong>state</strong> of a project. You can set your project to:\n<ul>\n	<li><strong>Send email normally</strong> - this emails your customers in a live environment.</li>\n	<li><strong>Not send any email</strong> - this will not send any emails, but will calculate and log events and campaigns as if you live.</li>\n	<li><strong>Only send email to a test address</strong> - this will send <strong>all emails</strong> to an email address you specify, so you can preview what your customers would receive.</li>\n</ul>\nTo change the <em>Delivery Settings</em> for project you are currently in, select the menu at the top left of the Vero menubar and `Edit delivery settings`.\n\n&nbsp;\n\nEvery account gets a free `<em>Sandbox` pr</em>oject<em>. </em>By default, your `Sandbox` project is set to <strong>not send any email</strong> to make it safe for you to test your campaign ideas without emailing any real customers.\n\nYou can easily switch between your projects using the navigator at the top left of the Vero menubar. Here''s an example of three projects. Note that the colored marker represents the <em>Delivery Settings</em> of each project.\n\n<a href="http://veropublic.staging.wpengine.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/02/Screen-Shot-2015-02-16-at-4.20.15-PM.png"><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-2212" src="http://veropublic.staging.wpengine.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/02/Screen-Shot-2015-02-16-at-4.20.15-PM.png" alt="Screen Shot 2015-02-16 at 4.20.15 PM" width="196" height="209" /></a>\n\n.', 'What is a project?', '', 'publish', 'closed', 'closed', '', 'what-is-a-project', '', '', '2015-02-13 09:45:22', '2015-02-13 09:45:22', '', 0, 'http://veropublic.staging.wpengine.com/?post_type=help_docs&amp;p=2178', 0, 'help_docs', '', 0),
(2180, 3, '2015-02-13 09:46:43', '2015-02-13 09:46:43', 'Triggered emails are always evaluated for sending when a user performs a specific <em>Event</em>. When you create an automated email must specify the ''base event'' that will triggered the email campaign.\n\nOn the <em>Behavioral</em> and <em>Transactional</em>campaign dashboards emails are, by default, grouped based on the event that triggers them.\n\nDETAILS ON LOGS.\n\n&nbsp;\n\n&nbsp;\n\n&nbsp;\n\n&nbsp;', 'How do I tell why a triggered (Transactional or Behavioral) email was or was not sent?', '', 'publish', 'closed', 'closed', '', 'how-do-i-tell-why-an-automated-triggered-email-was-sent', '', '', '2015-02-13 09:46:43', '2015-02-13 09:46:43', '', 0, 'http://veropublic.staging.wpengine.com/?post_type=help_docs&amp;p=2180', 0, 'help_docs', '', 0),
(2181, 3, '2015-02-13 09:53:31', '2015-02-13 09:53:31', 'You can individual contacts listed in a segment by going to the <em>Segments</em> menu and selecting `Edit &gt; View Users` next to any of your segments.\n\n<em>Edit</em> appears in the drop down associated with each segment, as below:\n\n<a href="http://veropublic.staging.wpengine.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/02/Screen-Shot-2015-02-16-at-2.02.51-PM.png"><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-2198" src="http://veropublic.staging.wpengine.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/02/Screen-Shot-2015-02-16-at-2.02.51-PM.png" alt="Screen Shot 2015-02-16 at 2.02.51 PM" width="1104" height="180" /></a>\n\nYou can also <em>Export</em> this list for use outside of Vero. To do this select `Export` at the top right, whilst on the <em>View Users </em>page. Here''s an example:\n\n&nbsp;\n\n<a href="http://veropublic.staging.wpengine.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/02/Screen-Shot-2015-02-16-at-2.50.46-PM.png"><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-2200" src="http://veropublic.staging.wpengine.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/02/Screen-Shot-2015-02-16-at-2.50.46-PM.png" alt="Screen Shot 2015-02-16 at 2.50.46 PM" width="918" height="54" /></a>', 'Can I see the individual contacts in a segment?', '', 'publish', 'closed', 'closed', '', 'can-i-see-the-individual-contacts-in-a-segment', '', '', '2015-02-13 09:53:31', '2015-02-13 09:53:31', '', 0, 'http://veropublic.staging.wpengine.com/?post_type=help_docs&amp;p=2181', 0, 'help_docs', '', 0),
(2182, 3, '2015-02-13 09:55:32', '2015-02-13 09:55:32', 'A base event is the original event that triggers a <em>Transactional</em> or <em>Behavioral</em> email campaign. If your triggered campaign has more than one email in series, the ''base event'' is the event that triggers <strong>Email 1</strong> of the series.\n\nAn example of this in practice is below.\n\nIf you create a <em>Behavioral </em>email campaign with multiple emails (a series campaign) where <strong>Email 1</strong> is triggered when a customer <strong>Adds a product to the cart</strong> then this is the event  be defined as the base event.\n\nWhen defining conditions in <strong>Email 2</strong> and <strong>Email 3 </strong>you can access data from the base event, even though the actual emails are actually triggered by the preceding email, rather than the base event itself.\n\n&nbsp;', 'What is a ''base event''?', '', 'publish', 'closed', 'closed', '', 'what-is-a-base-event', '', '', '2015-02-13 09:55:32', '2015-02-13 09:55:32', '', 0, 'http://veropublic.staging.wpengine.com/?post_type=help_docs&amp;p=2182', 0, 'help_docs', '', 0),
(2184, 3, '2015-02-13 09:59:52', '2015-02-13 09:59:52', '<a href="http://www.segment.com">Segment</a> is a flexible and fast alternative to setting up Vero. They are a customer data hub for easily installing analytics and growth tools. There are three reasons we like Segment at Vero:\n<ol>\n	<li>With one integration you can send the same customer data you send to Vero to over 100 other complementary services including KISSmetrics, Mixpanel, Woopra, Perfect Audience and many others.</li>\n	<li>If you want to integrate server-side, Segment offers client libraries for iOS, Android, Xamarin, Javascript, Ruby, Node.js, Python, PHP, Java, .NET, Go and Clojure. When you integrate with Segment, you don''t need to worry about updating any of these libraries - they take care of maintenance for you.</li>\n	<li>You can start using Segment with zero code via their one click-to-install plugins for many popular e-commerce and blogging platforms including <a href="https://segment.com/docs/platforms/magento/">Magento</a>, <a href="https://segment.com/docs/platforms/woocommerce/">WooCommerce</a>, <a href="https://segment.com/docs/platforms/wordpress/">WordPress</a>, <a href="https://segment.com/docs/platforms/wp-ecommerce/">WP eCommerce</a> and <a href="https://segment.com/docs/platforms/goodsie/">Goodsie</a>.</li>\n</ol>\nWe love the team at Segment and our integration is <strong>fully</strong> supported by both parties. To get going, <a href="https://segment.com/docs/integrations/vero/">read Segment''s docs for Vero setup.</a>', 'How do I integrate with Segment.com (formerly Segment.io)?', '', 'publish', 'closed', 'closed', '', '2184', '', '', '2015-02-13 09:59:52', '2015-02-13 09:59:52', '', 0, 'http://veropublic.staging.wpengine.com/?post_type=help_docs&amp;p=2184', 0, 'help_docs', '', 0),
(2185, 3, '2015-02-13 10:04:04', '2015-02-13 10:04:04', 'In Vero you can A/B test all of your email campaigns: <em>Newsletters, Transactional </em>emails and<em> Behavioral </em>emails<em>.</em>\n\nYou can A/B test:\n<ul>\n	<li>Subject lines,</li>\n	<li>From addresses,</li>\n	<li>Body content, and</li>\n	<li>Templates.</li>\n</ul>\nYou are also able to select the split rate for each variation.\n\nWhen running an A/B test on a <em>Behavioral</em> or <em>Transactional </em>email campaign that has more than one email (a series campaign), A/B tests <strong>run across the entire series</strong>. The split is decided with the first email in the series and the remaining emails follow suit.\n\nFor example, if a customer receives <em>Variation B</em> for the first email, they will receive Variation B throughout. This allows you to test entirely different templates or from addresses without your customers getting conflicting and inconsistent messages.', 'Can I A/B test my emails?', '', 'publish', 'closed', 'closed', '', 'can-i-ab-test-my-emails', '', '', '2015-02-13 10:04:04', '2015-02-13 10:04:04', '', 0, 'http://veropublic.staging.wpengine.com/?post_type=help_docs&amp;p=2185', 0, 'help_docs', '', 0),
(2186, 3, '2015-02-13 10:12:09', '2015-02-13 10:12:09', 'Using the <em>Templates</em> menu in Vero you can upload any custom HTML template you like. Vero fully supports media queries and responsive templates.\n\nOnce uploaded you can select and use a template in multiple email campaigns (newsletters, transactional, behavioral).\n\nTo ensure your templates are as flexible as possible, you need to mark which sections of the template should be updated when creating each new campaign. To mark a section as editable using our WYSIWYG editor, add the CSS class <em>vero-editable</em> to the <em>div</em>, <em>td</em> or<em> p</em> HTML tag you want editable. You can use our default templates as examples to see how they are structured.\n\nThis video will give you a good overview of how our templates work.\n\n[help_highlight_no_heading text="This video was shot using an older version of the Vero UI. We''re working on updating it as quickly as possible."]\n\nhttp://getvero.wistia.com/medias/mc4nmsdcf7?embedType=iframe&amp;videoWidth=800', 'How do I use HTML templates in Vero?', '', 'publish', 'closed', 'closed', '', 'how-do-i-use-html-templates-in-vero', '', '', '2015-02-13 10:12:09', '2015-02-13 10:12:09', '', 0, 'http://veropublic.staging.wpengine.com/?post_type=help_docs&amp;p=2186', 0, 'help_docs', '', 0),
(2188, 3, '2015-02-13 11:24:58', '2015-02-13 11:24:58', 'Liquid is an open-source, Ruby-based template language created by Shopify. We use it to load dynamic content in our emails based on data stored in the form of attributes. \n', 'What is the Liquid templating language?', '', 'publish', 'closed', 'closed', '', 'what-is-the-liquid-templating-language', '', '', '2015-02-13 11:24:58', '2015-02-13 11:24:58', '', 0, 'http://veropublic.staging.wpengine.com/?post_type=help_docs&amp;p=2188', 0, 'help_docs', '', 0),
(2189, 3, '2015-02-13 11:27:20', '2015-02-13 11:27:20', 'By default, Vero will handle your delivery for you, optimized to ensure your emails reach your users.\n\nVero also allows you to send your emails via some of your favourite transactional email provider, such as Sendgrid and Mailgun.\n\nTo use an alternate provider (and not Vero''s default setup), visit `Account &gt; Email Providers` and enter the appropriate credentials.\n\nHere you can currently select three options: <em>Vero''s delivery infrastructure, </em>Mailgun or Sendgrid.\n\nVero currently supports SendGrid and Mailgun. To enable the provider in question, simply select it from the list, enter your API credentials and hit Save and you''re good to go.\n\nIf you want support for other email providers, please <a href="mailto:support@getvero.com">email us via support</a>.', 'Can I use Sendgrid, Mailgun, Amazon SES, Mandrill or other providers for delivery?', '', 'publish', 'closed', 'closed', '', 'can-i-plug-in-sendgrid-mailgun-or-mandrill', '', '', '2015-02-13 11:27:20', '2015-02-13 11:27:20', '', 0, 'http://veropublic.staging.wpengine.com/?post_type=help_docs&amp;p=2189', 0, 'help_docs', '', 0),
(2193, 3, '2015-02-14 17:55:39', '2015-02-14 17:55:39', 'There are two key steps to getting setup with Vero:\n<ol>\n	<li>Tracking who your contacts are and what they are doing, and</li>\n	<li>Writing at least one campaign (we recommend a triggered campaign for maximum understanding of Vero).</li>\n</ol>\n<h2>Tracking who your contacts are and what they are doing</h2>\n<h3>Plug and play solutions</h3>\nTwo ways you can quickly get data into Vero include <a href="http://segment.com">Segment</a> and <a href="http://zapier.com">Zapier</a> (in beta, please <a href="mailto:support@getvero.com">email us</a> for instant access).\n\nIf you''re already setup on these platforms you''ll find them a quick way to get going, without installing Vero''s API directly (see below).\n<h3>Installing Vero on your site or in your app</h3>\nTo get the most value out of Vero you should install our API and track what your customers do on your website or in your application.\n\n[help_highlight title="FOR BEST RESULTS, INVOLVE YOUR DEVELOPER" text="You need some basic knowledge of HTML to get going with Vero. To get going the fastest, shoot this document to your developer (or shoot us an email at support@getvero.com)."]\n\nOur API has two key functions:\n<ol>\n	<li>Tracking a <em>contact</em> (user/customer/subscriber). We call this function <em>identifying</em> a user, and</li>\n	<li>Tracking what <em>actions</em> a contact takes. Actions are defined by you and typical examples would be things like <em>Views a product, Begins checkout, Uses a feature, Logs in, Subscribes to blog</em>, etc.</li>\n</ol>\nInstalling our API is most easily done using our <a href="/api">Javascript library</a>.\n<h3>Supported libraries</h3>\nYou can use Vero''s API with any coding language, but we currently have wrappers for these languages:\n<ul>\n	<li><a href="https://veropublic.staging.wpengine.com/api/ruby/">Ruby</a></li>\n	<li><a href="https://veropublic.staging.wpengine.com/api/python/">Python</a></li>\n	<li><a href="https://veropublic.staging.wpengine.com/api/php/">PHP</a></li>\n	<li><a href="https://veropublic.staging.wpengine.com/api/perl/">Perl</a></li>\n	<li><a href="https://veropublic.staging.wpengine.com/api/ios/">iOS</a></li>\n</ul>\nWe also have documentation on using the raw <a href="https://veropublic.staging.wpengine.com/api/http/">API end-points</a> via cURL or similar.\n<h2>Setting up your first campaign</h2>\nTo get the most value out of Vero you should setup a triggered campaign. These are automated emails that are triggered when a customer takes a certain action, so they work whilst you sleep.\n\nThere are three types of emails you can send in Vero:\n<ul>\n	<li><a href="http://veropublic.staging.wpengine.com/help/getting-started/behavioral-email-campaigns/" title="What is a behavioral campaign?">Behavioral</a> emails</li>\n	<li><a href="http://veropublic.staging.wpengine.com/help/getting-started/newsletter-email-campaigns/" title="What is a newsletter campaign?">Newsletters</a></li>\n	<li><a href="http://veropublic.staging.wpengine.com/help/getting-started/transactional-email-campaigns/" title="What is a transactional campaign?">Transactional</a> emails</li>\n</ul>\nThis video shows you how to setup your first Vero campaign in a few short steps:\n\n[help_highlight_no_heading text="This video uses an older version of the Vero UI. We''re working on updating it as quickly as possible!"]\n\nhttp://getvero.wistia.com/medias/ek6q63w3xf?embedType=iframe&amp;videoWidth=800', 'How to install Vero', '', 'publish', 'closed', 'closed', '', 'how-to-install-vero', '', '', '2015-02-14 17:55:39', '2015-02-14 17:55:39', '', 0, 'http://veropublic.staging.wpengine.com/?post_type=help_docs&amp;p=2193', 0, 'help_docs', '', 0),
(2250, 3, '2015-02-21 04:24:05', '2015-02-21 04:24:05', '[help_highlight_no_heading text="A dedicated IP address is a unique internet address dedicated exclusively to a single hosting account. In the case of email this means we''ll send your emails from a solo, dedicated server."]\n\nVero works extremely hard to ensure a consistently high reputation of all our shared IP''s.\n\nThere are cases however where your situation or volume is best supported by a dedicated IP. This gives you complete control of your own sending reputation  as your reputation will be influenced solely by the quality of <strong>your own</strong> contacts list and emails.\n\nOnce you have <em>Verified your DNS</em>, Vero can assign you domain over to your own dedicated IP.\n\nOur deliverability team can provide tailored solutions based on your needs. Please <a href="mailto:support@getvero.com">contact us via our support desk</a>.', 'Can I have a Dedicated IP?', '', 'publish', 'closed', 'closed', '', 'can-i-have-a-dedicated-ip', '', '', '2015-02-21 04:24:05', '2015-02-21 04:24:05', '', 0, 'http://veropublic.staging.wpengine.com/?post_type=help_docs&amp;p=2250', 0, 'help_docs', '', 0),
(2252, 3, '2015-02-21 04:45:16', '2015-02-21 04:45:16', 'When a user is unsubscribed their profile and history will remain stored in Vero, however they will no longer receive any <em>Behavioral </em>or <em>Newsletter </em>emails.\n\nTo check whether an individual contact is unsubscribed, view their profile. A yellow bar at the top of the profile page indicates that the contact is unsubscribed:\n\n<a href="http://veropublic.staging.wpengine.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/02/Screen-Shot-2015-02-21-at-3.43.31-PM.png"><img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-2253" src="http://veropublic.staging.wpengine.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/02/Screen-Shot-2015-02-21-at-3.43.31-PM.png" alt="Screen Shot 2015-02-21 at 3.43.31 PM" width="1062" height="141" /></a>', 'How do I know if a user is unsubscribed.', '', 'publish', 'closed', 'closed', '', 'how-do-i-know-if-a-user-is-unsubscribed', '', '', '2015-02-21 04:45:16', '2015-02-21 04:45:16', '', 0, 'http://veropublic.staging.wpengine.com/?post_type=help_docs&amp;p=2252', 0, 'help_docs', '', 0),
(2255, 3, '2015-02-21 04:54:40', '2015-02-21 04:54:40', 'Vero <strong>does </strong>automatically unsubscribe emails that return with a <strong>hard bounce</strong>.\n\nA <strong>hard bounce</strong> is an email message that is rejected by the recipient ISP/ESP because the recipient''s email address is invalid. A hard bounce might occur because the domain name doesn''t exist or because the recipient is unknown.\n\nVero <strong>does not</strong> automatically unsubscribe emails that return a <strong>soft bounce</strong>.\n\nThis is because a soft bounce is a a <strong>temporary</strong> delivery failure. The email has gotten as far as the recipient''s mail server but is returned as undelivered at least once before it is, ultimately, accepted and delivered to the recipients inbox.\n\nA <strong>soft bounce</strong> can occur for a number of reasons:\n<ul>\n	<li>The recipient''s mailbox is full</li>\n	<li>The receiving server is down or swamped with messages</li>\n	<li>The message size is too large</li>\n	<li>The recipient''s settings do not allow for email from the sender</li>\n	<li>Suspicious or spammy content has been detected</li>\n</ul>\n[help_highlight_no_heading text="When an email address returns a <strong>soft bounce</strong> for five consecutive campaigns we <strong>do</strong> automatically convert this to a <strong>hard bounce</strong> and unsubscribe the contact. "]', 'Does Vero automatically unsubscribe emails that have ''bounced''?', '', 'publish', 'closed', 'closed', '', 'does-vero-automatically-unsubscribe-emails-that-have-bounced', '', '', '2015-02-21 04:54:40', '2015-02-21 04:54:40', '', 0, 'http://veropublic.staging.wpengine.com/?post_type=help_docs&amp;p=2255', 0, 'help_docs', '', 0),
(2257, 3, '2015-02-21 05:02:04', '2015-02-21 05:02:04', 'When an email bounces, Vero records the details as part of the <em>Logs,</em> including the SMTP error returned by the recipients ISP/ESP, the number of times Vero attempted delivery and when this occurred.\n\nTo see this data, select an email in the logs and choose `View email data` from the options dropdown. An example is below:\n\n<a href="http://veropublic.staging.wpengine.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/02/view-email-data.png"><img class="alignnone wp-image-2290 size-full" src="http://veropublic.staging.wpengine.com/wp-content/uploads/2015/02/view-email-data.png" alt="view-email-data" width="1221" height="283" /></a>\n\nIf you ever have any questions about a bounced email please <a href="support@getvero.com">email support</a> and we''ll help you dig deeper!', 'Can I see why a specific email has bounced?', '', 'publish', 'closed', 'closed', '', 'can-i-see-why-a-specific-email-has-bounced', '', '', '2015-02-21 05:02:04', '2015-02-21 05:02:04', '', 0, 'http://veropublic.staging.wpengine.com/?post_type=help_docs&amp;p=2257', 0, 'help_docs', '', 0);
