(4992, 3, '2015-01-29 04:53:58', '2015-01-29 04:53:58', 'A/B testing gives you the power to test your email marketing hypotheses and<span>optimize your campaigns on an ongoing basis.</span>A/B testing is what separates a basic email marketer from a pro.\n\nVero gives you tools to A/B test both<em>newsletters</em>and<em>automated</em>campaigns with ease.\n<h3>Setting up an A/B test on an automated campaign</h3>\nYou can A/B test the<em>from address,</em><em>subject line</em>and<em>email contents</em>(rich text or HTML template) of any campaign.\n\nTo add a variation to an email campaign, view the campaign snapshot of a saved campaign and you''ll see the option to<span>Start an A/B test</span>at the top right.<img src="https://www.getvero.com/assets/docs/ab-tests/start-89410f2ce6fe7561fc61f10d03f3e467.png" alt="Start" />\n<div class="highlight">\n<h5>DID YOU KNOW?</h5>\nIf you have already started an A/B test you can edit it at any time by returning to the campaign snapshot screen. Instead of seeing<em>Start an A/B test</em>you''ll see a button to<em>Edit A/B test.</em>\n\n</div>\nThe A/B test editor allows you to quickly and easily add variations to your emails. When you add a variation it is added to<span>all of the emails in your campaign,</span>even if you have multiple emails in your series.\n\nBy default each new variation will have the same from address, subject and content as the Control (base) email variation. By adding the variation across the entire series, you are able to A/B test your campaign holistically. If a customer gets<em>Variation A</em>for the first email in the series, Vero will<span>automatically ensure</span>that they get<em>Variation A</em>throughout the rest of the campaign.\n\nThis helps you safely A/B test different templates or from addresses consistenly, which is key to a unified user experience.\n\nTo make changes to the from address or subject line, simply click the text and it will become editable, like so:<img src="https://www.getvero.com/assets/docs/ab-tests/edit-subject-19a8018bb919d0d3afe809fa1f8f7be6.png" alt="Edit-subject" />\n\nTo edit the body of the email click the ''Edit'' button on the right hand side next to a variation.\n\nOnce you are happy scroll to the bottom and select<em>Put A/B test live</em>or<em>Update A/B test</em>to get your test going.\n<h3>Setting up an A/B test on a newsletter campaign</h3>\nLearn<a href="https://www.getvero.com/docs/docs/newsletter-email-campaigns">how to create a newsletter campaign</a>using the guide in these docs.\n\nOnce you have saved a draft of your newsletter you can add variations to it. To do this, edit the campaign again and scroll to the content area. Here you will see the option to "Add a variation":<img src="https://www.getvero.com/assets/docs/ab-tests/newsletter-var-abc7bb2141de84b8f6aae866612c8887.png" alt="Newsletter-var" />\n\nYou can then edit the variation the same as you would edit the control. When you are happy, ensure you select<span>Save variation</span>at the bottom of the newsletter. If you do not do this your<span>changes will be lost.</span>\n\n<span>Note:</span>If you switch between variation tabs and have not saved the changes to a variation, you will lose your changes. Vero will warn you when you try to do this and haven''t saved your variation yet.\n<h3>Negative variations</h3>\nA/B tests on automated campaigns also give you the option to create a<span>negative variation.</span>\n\nA negative variation allows you to define a percentage of customers that<span>will not</span>receive the email or email series. Vero will still track the conversinos for these customers, i.e. if they take the goal of the campaign, and report on it.\n\nNegative variations are designed to help you assess whether your campaigns are leading to increased conversions, decreased conversions or make no difference at all.\n<div class="did-you-know">\n<h5>DID YOU KNOW?</h5>\nWhen viewing the<a href="https://www.getvero.com/docs/reporting">report data</a>for a campaign, a negative variation will show up just like any other variation. Open and click data is not applicable so will be blank. Conversions will still be tracked.\n\n</div>\n<h3>Setting split percentages</h3>\nRegardless of whether you''re testing an automated or newsletter campaign you can easily define the split percentages for each campaign. This determines what percentage of customers get each variation.\n\nTo define the split percentage edit your A/B test (automated campaigns) or the campaign itself (newsletter campaigns) and scroll to the bottom. You will see an option to define the split percentages of each variation.<img src="https://www.getvero.com/assets/docs/ab-tests/splits-a103d016ef00c45a822bec78133bd65f.png" alt="Splits" />\n\nSave your A/B test for the changes to the split percentages to take effect.', 'A/B Tests', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '82-autosave-v1', '', '', '2015-01-29 04:53:58', '2015-01-29 04:53:58', '', 82, 'http://localhost:8888/82-autosave-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
